{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L9tmzvvLxZj9SgG3vm4FnF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The CA cert is the same. So the issue must be something else. The CA cert in the secret matches the toolbox. The new node cert is signed by the same CA. The old node cert is also signed by the same CA. So TLS should work between the pods...\n\nWait, let me think again. Maybe the issue is that the rolling restart is making pods 0 and 1 also restart, but by the time they come up, they have the new ca.crt and new node.crt. But then pod 2 is presenting its new cert to pods 0 and 1 (which may be running with old certs still loaded in memory), and pods 0/1 reject pod 2's new cert because... \n\nActually, that doesn't hold up if the CA is the same. Let me look at this from pod 2's perspective—it's failing to establish a gossip connection to pod 1, which suggests the handshake is breaking down somewhere. Maybe the issue is that the secret volumes are being dynamically updated by kubelet on the running pods, but the process hasn't fully reloaded the new certificates from disk, creating some kind of mismatch between what's in memory and what's on the filesystem.\n\nLooking at the actual error: pod 2 is trying to connect to pod 0 and pod 1, presenting its own certificate for verification. Pod 2 was restarted after the secret update, so it's loaded the new CA and node certificates. But pod 0 still has the old certificates in memory from its startup before the update happened. So when pod 2 tries to verify pod 0's old certificate against its new CA, the verification fails because they're from different certificate chains.\n\nWait, but I just confirmed the old and new CA certificates are identical. So that shouldn't be the issue. Let me think about whether CockroachDB actually reloads certificates dynamically on new connections, or if it only loads them at startup.\n\nActually, if CockroachDB does reload certs on each new connection, then pods 0 and 1 would pick up the new certificates from the updated secret mount even without restarting. In that case, the certificate chain should verify correctly in both directions. So the TLS errors might be stale from before the secret was updated on disk, and the real problem preventing pod 2 from becoming ready could be something else entirely—like a quorum or Raft leadership issue rather than certificate verification.\n\nLooking at the logs, pod 2 is reporting that all nodes are down and it's lost quorum, and the gossip connections to pods 0 and 1 are failing with TLS errors. So pod 2 can't establish quorum because those gossip connections keep failing.\n\nBut checking the pod status, pods 0 and 1 are both running and ready with 10 minutes of uptime, while pod 2 is not ready and only 7 minutes old. This means pods 0 and 1 can still communicate with each other and maintain quorum as a pair. Pod 2 is stuck because it can't connect to them due to the TLS certificate verification failures.\n\nI'm wondering if the secret volume might have already been auto-refreshed on pods 0 and 1 by the kubelet, and they're now using the new certificates dynamically. If so, there could be an issue with the certificate extensions or SANs that CockroachDB requires. Let me compare the Subject Alternative Names between the new and old certificates to see what's different.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":949,"cache_read_input_tokens":55709,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":949},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9db65659-7646-4124-8edc-f420fd8e6e18","uuid":"441f62b9-018f-45c8-aff8-83576edd47b5","request_id":"req_011CcekpkvrsNDyGpBKe7C3p"}
