{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Gc7ijeEoCBUUn8wisPAyKW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The extensions and SANs look identical between the old and new certs. The Authority Key Identifier is the same (BA:3C:D9:D8:72:3B:7B:BB:AF:9D:3B:5D:B7:95:98:67:59:3B:8C:50), confirming they're both signed by the same CA.\n\nThe issue must be something else. Let me think...\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the error message from crdb-cluster-2 more carefully:\n\n```\nfailed to start gossip client to crdb-cluster-0...: initial connection heartbeat failed: \ngrpc: connection error: desc = \"transport: authentication handshake failed: \ntls: failed to verify certificate: x509: certificate signed by unknown authority \n(possibly because of \\\"crypto/rsa: verification error\\\" while trying to verify \ncandidate authority certificate \\\"CockroachDB CA\\\")\"\n```\n\nThe key phrase here is \"while trying to verify candidate authority certificate 'CockroachDB CA'\" — this means the verification is failing on the CA certificate itself, not the node certificate. The server is presenting a certificate chain that includes the CA cert, and the client can't verify it. This suggests CockroachDB is including the CA in the chain, which means the client needs to have that CA cert in its trust store to validate it.\n\nThe error could stem from either the CA cert not being trusted or the CA cert's own signature failing RSA verification. Since it's self-signed, Go's TLS stack would try to verify its own signature, and if that fails, the whole chain fails. I'm wondering if the newly generated node.crt was bundled differently than the original — maybe it's missing the CA cert or has it in a different format. I should check whether the old node.crt included just the leaf certificate or also bundled the CA, and whether the pods are actually reloading the certificates at startup or if they're cached.\n\nThe real issue might be timing: pods 0 and 1 started before the secret update and loaded the old certificates, then the kubelet updated the mounted files, but when pod 2 connects and tries to verify the new node.crt with its new ca.crt, there could be a race condition if the kubelet hasn't finished updating all the volumes consistently. But that doesn't explain why the failure persists. I'm thinking the rolling restart approach might not be working because the StatefulSet requires each pod to be ready before moving to the next one, and if the cert verification is failing, the pods won't become ready.\n\nThe better approach is to delete all three pods simultaneously so they restart together with the new certificates from the secret, breaking the deadlock where pod 2 can't become ready without the others also having the new certs. Let me also verify what's actually happening on the gossip connection—maybe there's something about how the in-memory CA is being used that I'm missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3359,"cache_read_input_tokens":56658,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3359},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9db65659-7646-4124-8edc-f420fd8e6e18","uuid":"f8af675f-1918-408e-868c-770d79a61b74","request_id":"req_011Cceks6Uf6WA9J3SFMGn2D"}
